But the way to the cosmos of Poland began a long time ago.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts traveled to space, but this did not always meet with understanding.
I recall, for example, the lecture A. Sternfeld, which on 6 December 1933 presented to the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory the idea of his innovative work "Introduction to Cosmonautique".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905) left the audience with an equal heart, and after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won Robert Esno-Peltri and Andre Luis Hirsch's "Introduction to Cosmonautique".
Dr. Jan Gadomsky (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a major advocate of astronomy and cosmonautique.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
The Chadomian became known as a world advocate of cosmonautism, and his contribution was assessed, including that one of the craters on the other side of the Moon was named in his honor.
Already in 1925, a railway vehicle equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Regrettably, the author of the idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear that a missile should have been used for the decommissioning or braking of the body.
Information on this site is only known from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery has begun to think about rockets.
The study was conducted by the Arms Technology Section, in cooperation with Professors Michislav Wolfe and Gustav Mozzicki.
The remaining materials show that the studies have reached the stage of practical tests.
But with the arrival of the German forces, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, a special press released the idea of a photo-electric missile by Rogosinski and the following year, the work of the "Air Torpedo and Aviation Bomb" by the author, Leviva-Kzjoblockko, was released.
Both projects have been developed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war itself, all projects of military use of missile technology were undertaken by the Temporary Scientific and Advisory Committee (Timely Adradczo-Naukowy) which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work, the work was completed as a result of the beginning of the war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautique appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautique Society (Polish Association of Astronautique).
For the first time, the issue of society was mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the “Problems” magazine, which published four large articles on astronomy.
In one of them, Professor M. Sobotovic proposed to organize a society that would deal with spacecraft.
At the time, the projects of artificial satellites were already under way, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronomical Society (POA) has tried to enter the international astronomical federation (based in 1951) and has already become a member of the APO in autumn.
And next year, the first President of POA Kazimež Zarankevic (1902 - 1959) became Vice President of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in that post until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, POA has made a significant contribution to the development of a very successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which has become the first Polish rocket to conduct a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first started on 10 October 1958.
The rocket capable of overcoming the distance of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of RM-1A was subsequently built, and two-stage RM-2 rocket tests were conducted in the Bledwood Desert in 1959.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already capable of carrying out the current scientific work - the RM-34 missile could exceed 14.5 km and its task was to monitor the high winds.
But further development was suspended in 1962.
The first RM-type successor was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-step, its total length was 510 cm and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (known as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) have been developed, which differ in the size of the camera for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had an area of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B - 0.34 litres, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 litres.
The maximum length of the flight in all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first summer tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with an initial weight of 380 kg was able to carry a useful load of 10 kg at a height of about 60 km.
Then the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR ( Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space research on Soviet artistic satellites, and in 1978, Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaschevski became the second intercosmonate after Vladimir Remek.
