Sabo: "Germans must play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, an expert on U.S. and Europe's links, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first admitted that it had voted against the Palestinians ' request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained in the vote.
Why?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be cautious about its special relations with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence, while not being too critical of Israel.
At the time of the rise in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a restricted zone for flights.
As a result, NATO has put forward this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
The case is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, and that is to say, it is from a policy that has been governed by the United States to a German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a unified policy.
Thus, the Germans are again placed between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that while they are just grasping their role, they are on their way to "better normal" foreign policy.
Such an external policy that France or the United Kingdom pursues.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean in German terms?
It is a willingness to take a position that is not dependent on the position of the United States or European partners in their national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is dependent on economic policy, that is, on exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ significantly from those of other major States, and Germany should therefore protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
First, Germany has major trading markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf States.
It should therefore be cautious not to offend the public and the elite in the Arab countries.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't give too much importance to that, it's not a completely unilateral relationship.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Did Germany harm its relations with the United States by abstaining from important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, there is an understanding of the German position.
That's why I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan question.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This indicates that it should be taken seriously as a game on the international stage and that it should be considered to be of interest.
There are various views on the Palestinian initiative in Europe.
On the contrary, the United States had clearly stated the veto.
Is there a distinction between the United States and many European States?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has a deep understanding of the European position.
But, of course, in the context of the local political situation, the Government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that significant differences in opinion are not as important as it always seems.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, note that Obama is not at all stubbornly opposed to Netanyahu's policy.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close relationship with Israel and the United States on the one hand and the situation of the key partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, Germans would be slightly simpler if there were a single, non-controversial European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and are forced to act instead, based only on their own vision.
That is how they come from the euro.
I think that Germany will play a leading role in developing a common European position in the future.
It is understandable that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of relations with Israel.
This subject has always been subtle.
But I think it is clear to the Germans that they must play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, won't it really play a major role?
Or is the leading role still difficult for Germany?
Germany has not been used to this, and it is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany assumes an important role, the most diverse anti-German feelings are expressed.
The Germans aren't just dealing with it.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult situation than the United States.
It should take into account the different neighbours and views, and that was not easy.
Thus, the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly weakening, but at this point the EU does not fill this vacuum, but who remains?
The Germans would simply have to play a more important role.
Even if you do not like it, it makes you feel uncomfortable or makes you feel unloved.
Stephen Sabo, Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly investigate the problems of the transatlantic community.
